[2] Missouri (Springfield, Greene county)
Date: Tue 28 Feb 2012
Source: News-Leader [summ., edited]
http://www.news-leader.com/article/20120228/NEWS01/302280038


The Springfield-Greene County Health Department said Mon 27 Feb 2012, that it is seeing an increase in cases of whooping cough. In a news release, the health department said it has confirmed 4 cases of whooping cough in recent weeks. 3 of the cases were infants less than a year old; the other was an adult.

"While the number of cases is not especially large, any such spike is notable because of the highly contagious nature of the disease," the release said. "The situation is compounded by an alarming lack of immunizations among infants in these recent cases."

Infants and young children are at the highest risk of life-threatening consequences. More than half of infants younger than one year of age who get the disease must be hospitalized. Of those infants who are hospitalized for pertussis, about one in 5 will get pneumonia and about one in 100 will die, according to the CDC.

